DNA HELICAL GEOMETRY
This document presents a mathematical framework for understanding 
DNA structure through the lens of Recursive Geometric Dynamics (RDG).

I. GENERIC HELICAL MODEL
──────────────────────
DNA's helical structure can be described as a screw operator in 3D 
space—a combination of rotation about the z-axis and translation 
along it. The same generator applies to all DNA forms (A, B, C, and Z).

Backbone Curve
Backbone curve: Parametric equations describe the helix using radius 
(R), pitch (P), and angular parameter (t)

              ⎡ R cos(t) ⎤
r(t) =        ⎢ R sin(t) ⎥
              ⎢  P·t     ⎥
              ⎣ ──────  ⎦
                2π

Parameters:
R = helix radius
P = pitch (height per full turn)
t = angular parameter

Left-handed Z-DNA

              ⎡ R cos(t) ⎤
r(t) =        ⎢-R sin(t) ⎥
              ⎢  P·t     ⎥
              ⎣ ──────  ⎦
                2π


II. SCREW OPERATOR
──────────────────
Screw operator σ = (Rz(θ), h): Rotation by angle θ and translation by 
height h

Repeated application of this operator constructs the full double 
helix as a cyclic subgroup of SE(3) (Special Euclidean group)

Single generator:

σ = S(θ,h)

S(θ,h) = Rz(θ) · Tz(h)

Rz(θ) = rotation about z-axis
Tz(h) = translation along z-axis

Iteration rule:

xₙ₊₁ = S(θ,h)xₙ
gₙ   = g₀ σⁿ

This defines a cyclic subgroup of SE(3).

III. ATOMIC ORBITS
────────────────

Initial atomic coordinates:

(rᵢ, φᵢ, zᵢ)

After n iterations:

xᵢ,n = Rz(nθ)xᵢ,0 + [0, 0, nh]ᵀ

Projection:

(x,y,z) → (x,y)

produces orbit rosettes:

           ✶ ✶ ✶ ✶ ✶
      ✶                 ✶
   ✶                       ✶
  ✶                         ✶
   ✶                       ✶
      ✶                 ✶
           ✶ ✶ ✶ ✶ ✶

These are the “flower” symmetry patterns.


IV. DNA PARAMETER SETS
───────────────────
DNA Conformations
All four DNA forms use the same generator but with different parameters:

bp/turn     Rotation      Handedness

A-DNA       11         +32.7°         Right
B-DNA      10.5        +34.3°         Right
C-DNA       9.3        +38.7°         Right
Z-DNA       12         -30.0°         Left

Changing only:

R, P, θ, h

changes the conformation.

The generator σ remains the same.


V. GROUP THEORY
──────────────

Generator:

σ = (Rz(θ), h)

Repeated application:

σ⁰, σ¹, σ², σ³, …

constructs the full double helix.

DNA is therefore a discrete screw subgroup of SE(3).


