IX. CONCLUSION
─────────────────
Rather than treating each DNA form as structurally distinct, the RDG 
interpretation shows they're all parameterizations of a single 
screw-symmetry process—only R, P, θ, and h values change, while 
the underlying generator remains constant.

Same recursive generator
        ↓
Different parameter sets
        ↓
Different helical conformations
        ↓
Different projected orbit geometries
        ↓
Different curvature signatures

DNA forms A, B, C, and Z are parameterizations of a single screw-
symmetry process in SE(3), making DNA a natural instance of RDG 
recursive geometric dynamics.

Projecting atomic orbits creates characteristic "flower" symmetry 
patterns that serve as curvature signatures for each conformation.
